:QUOTE
A sharp knife is safer than a dull one. Most cuts from kitchen knives come from forcing a blunt edge.

:INFO
What Sharpening Actually Does
A knife edge is a microscopic wedge. Over time that wedge rolls, chips, and \
folds under use. Sharpening removes metal from both faces of the blade until \
they meet at a new, aligned apex. The result is a thinner, keener edge that \
cuts by slicing rather than tearing.

:COUNTER.half
15 Degrees Per Side
Japanese knives
|
:COUNTER.half
20 Degrees Per Side
Western knives

:INFO
The Angle Is Everything
Hold the blade at the correct angle to the stone and maintain it through \
every stroke. Japanese knives (Gyuto, Santoku) use 15 degrees per side. \
German and French knives use 20 degrees. A 15-degree angle is roughly \
the thickness of two stacked credit cards placed under the spine at the heel.

:PATH
Prepare the Stone
Soak a coarse or medium stone (below 2000 grit) in water for 5 to 10 minutes \
until bubbles stop rising. Fine finishing stones (3000 grit and above) only \
need a splash of water on the surface. Keep a small spray bottle nearby to \
rewet as you work. A dry stone cuts slower and glazes over quickly.

:PATH
Set Your Angle and Start Sharpening
Place the stone on a damp towel to prevent slipping. Hold the knife edge toward \
the stone, spine raised to your target angle. Apply medium pressure with two \
or three fingertips on the flat of the blade. Push the edge forward along the \
stone as if slicing a thin layer off the top. Lift slightly at the tip to follow \
the curve. Repeat 6 to 8 strokes, then switch sides.

:INFO
Feeling for the Burr
A burr is a thin wire of metal that folds to the opposite side as you sharpen. \
Run a thumb across the edge at 90 degrees, not along it. You should feel a slight \
roughness or catch on the side you have not sharpened. Once the burr runs \
consistently from heel to tip, switch sides and repeat. The burr tells you you \
have reached the apex.

:COUNTER.half
6 to 8 Strokes
Per side to raise a full burr
|
:COUNTER.half
Lighter Pressure Only
On fine finishing grits

:PATH
Remove the Burr on Fine Grit
Move to your finishing stone (6000 grit or higher). Alternate one stroke per \
side using decreasing pressure. This deburrs the edge and refines the apex. \
Five to eight alternating strokes is usually enough. Finish with two or three \
very light edge-trailing strokes to align any remaining metal.

:PATH
Strop to Finish
Strop the edge on a piece of leather, dense cardboard, or the spine of a \
paperback book. Ten passes per side, edge trailing, at the same angle as \
sharpening. Stropping realigns the apex without removing metal and adds a \
noticeable jump in sharpness that stones alone cannot deliver.

:CHECKLIST
Setup Before You Start
[ ] Stone soaked or wetted to match grit (coarse soaks, fine splashes)
[ ] Damp towel under the stone to prevent movement
[ ] Spray bottle of water within reach
[ ] Target angle identified (15 degrees or 20 degrees)
[ ] Strop or cardboard ready for finishing

:NOTE
The Paper Test
Slice through a sheet of printer paper using the full length of the blade. A \
sharp edge cuts cleanly and quietly with no tearing. A polished edge on a \
fine stone cuts with almost no sound at all. Run this test at any stage to \
track your progress. If the paper folds or deflects, the edge still needs work.

:QUOTE
Sharpening is a conversation between your angle and the stone. Consistency matters more than pressure.

